                                               User Stories

                                  Authentication & Profile Management
                                     Actor : End User / Admin

User Story 1: User Registration

Front of the card:
As a new user, I want to sign up using my email and password, so that I can create an account and access the system.

Back of the card:
● User can provide a unique email and password.
● Password must meet security rules (min length, special characters).
● Account gets created only if details are valid.
● Error shown if email already exists.


User Story 2: User Login

Front of the card:
As a registered user, I want to log in securely with my credentials, so that I can access my personal account.

Back of the card:
● User can log in with valid email and password.
● Invalid credentials are rejected with an error message.
● Successful login starts a new session.
● Login attempts are rate-limited to prevent brute force attacks.


User Story 3: Social Login

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to sign in using my social media accounts, so that I can log in quickly without creating a new password.

Back of the card:
● Support Google and apple login via OAuth.
● Successful authentication creates or links to an account.
● Login failures handled gracefully with appropriate messages.


User Story 4: Password Recovery

Front of the card:
As a user who forgot my password, I want to reset it via email verification, so that I can regain access to my account.

Back of the card:
● Password reset request triggers reset password link sent through email.
● User enters and confirms new password.
● User can now login with new password.
● Old password becomes invalid after reset.
● Reset link expires after a limited time.


User Story 5: Secure SignOut

Front of the card:
As a logged-in user, I want to sign out from the system, so that I can ensure no one else accesses my account.

Back of the card:
● User session ends immediately on sign out.
● Tokens/cookies invalidated on the server.
● User redirected to login page after logout.
● Logout option available on all screens.


User Story 6: View Profile

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to view my profile information, so that I can see my account details clearly.

Back of the card:
● Profile displays name, email, subscriptions, and activity.
● Data retrieved securely from the database.
● Profile page accessible only to authenticated users.
● Unauthorized access blocked with error/redirect.


User Story 7: Update Profile

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to edit my profile details, so that I can keep my information up to date.

Back of the card:
● User can update username, password, and profile picture.
● Changes saved to the database and confirmed with a message.
● Updates validated before saving (e.g., strong password rules).
● System prevents updating with duplicate email/username.


User Story 8: Security Notifications

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to get notified when my account is accessed from a new device, so that I can protect my account against unauthorized access.

Back of the card:
● System detects and logs new device/browser logins.
● Notification sent via email for new device access.
● User can review device activity from account settings.
● Option to block or sign out suspicious sessions.

User Story 9: Admin Authentication

Front of the card:
As an admin, I want to log in with secure admin credentials, so that I can manage books, authors, and users safely.

Back of the card:
● Admin login page is same as user login.
● Only accounts with admin role can access the dashboard.
● Failed login attempts logged for security monitoring.
● Admin sessions end securely on logout.
● Admin password policies stricter than regular users.



                                             Admin & Analytics
                                           Actor : Admin/Manager

User Story 1: Manage Books

Front of the card:
As an Admin, I want to add, update, or remove books, so that the bookstore’s catalog always stays relevant and accurate.

Back of the card:
● Admin can upload book details (title, author, publisher, genre, price, cover image, description).
● Admin can edit existing book details.
● Admin can remove books from the catalog.
● Changes should be reflected instantly in the user-facing store.
● System validates data before saving (e.g., price must be numeric, cover image must be a valid format).


User Story 2: Manage Reviews

Front of the card:
As an Admin, I want to monitor and remove inappropriate reviews, so that the platform maintains quality and credibility.

Back of the card:
● Admin can view all user reviews.
● Admin can flag/remove reviews containing offensive or irrelevant content.
● Admin can restore mistakenly deleted reviews (soft delete).
● Admin can filter reviews by book, rating, or date.
● Notifications sent to users if their review is removed.


User Story 3: Manage Authors & Publishers

Front of the card:
As an Admin, I want to add and manage author and publisher information, so that books are accurately categorized and linked
to their creators.

Back of the card:
● Admin can add author details (name, bio, photo, nationality, genre).
● Admin can add publisher details (name, logo, description, location).
● Admin can edit/update author and publisher information.
● Books can be linked to the respective author and publisher.
● Admin can deactivate authors/publishers if no longer active.


User Story 4: Analytics & Trends

Front of the card:
As a Manager, I want to view analytics on current trends and user preferences, so that I can make data-driven business 
decisions.


Back of the card:
● System displays most purchased books, most viewed books, and top-rated books.
● Manager can see user demographics (age, location, genre preferences).
● Graphs/charts showing trends over time (weekly, monthly, yearly).
● AI-driven insights on upcoming popular genres.
● Data export option (CSV/PDF) for reports.



                                         Reading & Progress Tracking
                                              Actor: End User

User Story 1: Reading Books

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to open and read a book in the app so that I can enjoy the content directly within the platform.

Back of the card:
● From the catalogue, clicking a book opens the reader interface.
● The system loads the book content (text, EPUB/PDF) in a responsive reading view.
● User can navigate between chapters/pages using scroll or navigation controls.
● Book content is formatted for readability (font size, background theme options).
● Reading progress is automatically tracked as the user moves through the content.

User Story 2: Marking a Book as Read

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to mark a book as "Read" so that I can keep track of books I have completed.

Back of the card:
● A “Mark as Read” button/option must be visible on the book’s detail page and inside the reader.
● Clicking it updates the user’s library status in Firestore (users/{uid}/library).
● Once marked, the book appears in the “Books Read” section of the profile.
● The status can be updated again (e.g., changed back to “Reading” if needed).

User Story 3: Marking a Book to Read in the Future

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to add a book to my "To Read" list so that I can plan future reading.

Back of the card:
● A “Save to To-Read List” button must be visible on the book’s detail page.
● Clicking it saves the book’s ID to the user’s Firestore library with status to_read.
● The “To Read” list is accessible from the user profile/dashboard.
● The user can remove the book from the list or change its status anytime.

User Story 4: Viewing Books Read

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to view a list of all books I’ve read so that I can see my completed reading history.

Back of the card:
● The “Books Read” section is accessible from the user profile.
● It displays a list/grid of all books marked with status read.
● Each entry shows cover image, title, author, and date completed.
● The user can click any book to revisit its details or open it again.
● The system updates this list in real time when new books are marked as read.

User Story 5: Cross-Device Sync

Front of the card:
As a user, I want my reading progress, bookmarks, and highlights to sync across devices so that I can continue reading seamlessly.

Back of the card:
● The system stores progress/bookmarks/highlights in Firestore under users/{uid}.
● Progress is auto-synced every few seconds or on chapter change.
● When the user opens the same book on another device, the system loads the last saved progress automatically.
● If progress differs between devices, the system resolves by using the most recent update (updatedAt field).
● Bookmarks and notes are synced in real time, ensuring consistency across devices.

                                          Engagement & Community
                                             Actor: End User

User Story 1: Rating the Book

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to give a star rating to a book I’ve read, so that I can express my overall opinion and help other readers decide if they want to read it.

Back of the card:
● User can select a rating (e.g., 1–5 stars).
● The system saves the rating to the book.
● Average rating of the book updates automatically.
● User can update/change their rating.

User Story 2: Uploading Reviews

Front of the card:
As an end user, I want to write and upload detailed reviews of books I read, so that I can share my thoughts, experiences, and recommendations with the community.

Back of the card:
● User can type a text review and submit it.
● Review gets displayed below the correct book.
● Reviews are displayed publicly for other readers.
● User can edit or delete their own review.

User Story 3: Discussing About the Book

Front of the card:
As an end user, I want to participate in discussions and comment on books I read, so that I can exchange perspectives.

Back of the card:
● User can comment on books or reviews.
● Discussion threads display in proper order.
● Users can reply to others’ comments.
● Notifications are sent when someone replies.

User Story 4: Bookmarking & Notes

Front of the card:
As an end user, I want to bookmark pages and add notes, so that I can continue where I left off and revisit important sections later.

Back of the card:
● User can bookmark a page in a book.
● Notes can be attached to bookmarks.
● Bookmarks and notes are saved persistently.
● User can view and manage (edit/delete) bookmarks & notes.

User Story 5: Highlighting

Front of the card:
As an end user, I want to highlight passages or words, so that I can mark meaningful content for later reference.

Back of the card:
● User can select text and apply highlights.
● Highlighted text is saved and shown on revisit.
● User can remove or change highlight color.
● Highlights are stored per book and per user.


                                    Catalogue & Discovery 
                                      Actor: End User


User Story 1: Browse Catalogue by Genre

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to browse books by specific genres, so that I can discover new books when I'm in the mood for a certain type of story.

Back of the Card:
●A list of available genres is displayed on the 'Explore' page.
●Each genre in the list is clickable.
●Clicking a genre navigates to a new page that displays only books from that selected genre.
●The genre page has a title that clearly identifies the genre being viewed.


User Story 2: Basic Search

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to search for books by their title or an author's name, so that I can find exactly what I'm looking for without having to browse.

Back of the Card:
●A search bar is present and functional in the site header.
●Searching by a known book title returns that book in the results.
●Searching by a known author's name returns books by that author.
●A "No results found" message is shown for searches that have no matches.

User Story 3: View Trending Books

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to see a list of what's currently trending, so that I can stay up-to-date with popular books and see what others are enjoying.

Back of the Card:
●A section titled "Trending Now" is visible on the homepage.
●The section displays a collection of books.
●Clicking on any book within the section navigates to that book's detail page.

User Story 4: Find New Releases

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to easily find a dedicated section for 'New Releases,' so that I can keep up with the latest books as soon as they become available.

Back of the Card:
●A clickable link or section for "New Releases" is present on the homepage.
●The "New Releases" page displays books sorted with the newest publications first.
●Only books published within the last 30 days are included in this section.

User Story 5: Track Explored Books

Front of the Card:
As a curious reader, I want to see a personal statistic of how many books I've explored from the total catalogue, so that I can track my discovery journey on the platform.

Back of the Card:
●The user's profile page displays a counter showing "X out of Y books explored".
●The 'X' value increments by one after the user visits the detail page of a book for the first time.
●The counter does not increment when visiting a previously explored book's page again.


                                             Payments & Subscriptions
                                             Actor: End User + Admin

User Story 1: Subscribing to a Plan

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to subscribe to a plan so that I can access premium features of the service.

Back of the card:
● From the subscription page, clicking "Subscribe" opens the available plans.
● Details like plan duration, benefits, and price are visible.
● A plan can be selected and payment completed.
● On successful payment, subscription status updates to "Active."
● A confirmation email with subscription details is received.


User Story 2: Managing Subscription Plans

Front of the card:
As an admin, I want to manage subscription details so that plans and pricing remain accurate.

Back of the card:
● From the dashboard, clicking "Subscriptions" opens the management panel.
● Subscription plans can be created, edited, or deleted.
● Plan details like price, features, and duration can be updated.
● Validated changes are applied immediately.
● All modifications are recorded for future reference.


User Story 3: Completing Secure Payments

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to complete my payment securely so that my financial details remain safe.

Back of the card:
● From the checkout page, payment details are entered and "Pay Now" is clicked.
● Payment is processed through a secure gateway.
● Confirmation of successful payment is shown instantly.
● Receipt is generated and sent via email.
● Subscription or order status updates automatically.


User Story 4: Monitoring Secure Payments

Front of the card:
As an admin, I want to monitor and verify secure payments so that all transactions remain trustworthy.

Back of the card:
● From the dashboard, logs of successful payments are visible.
● Payment gateway responses can be verified.
● Daily, weekly, and monthly reports can be generated.
● Reports provide accurate revenue tracking.
● All payment records are stored for financial analysis.


User Story 5: Viewing Order History

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to check my previous subscription orders so that I can track my payments and renewals.

Back of the card:
● From the profile, "Order History" displays past subscriptions.
● Orders show details like plan name, amount paid, date, and status.
● History is sorted with most recent first.
● Cancelled orders are clearly labeled.
● If no orders exist, a message "No order history found" is displayed.


User Story 6: Maintaining Order History

Front of the card:
As an admin, I want to maintain accurate order history so that users always see correct records.

Back of the card:
● From the dashboard, user order histories can be accessed and verified.
● History can be filtered by user, date range, or plan type.
● Records are stored in database and kept consistent with payments.
● Order records can be updated when needed.
● Backups of order history are maintained for compliance.


User Story 7: Analyzing Retention Data

Front of the card:
As an admin, I want to analyze retention data so that I can improve subscription renewals and reduce churn.

Back of the card:
● From the dashboard, "Retention Data" opens the analytics module.
● Metrics like renewal rate, churn rate, and active users are available.
● Reports can be filtered by time period, plan type, or user segment.
● Visual graphs display retention trends.
● Reports can be exported in CSV or PDF for analysis.


                                                        Personalization & Recommendations
                                                        Actors: End User + System (AI)

User Story 1 – Selecting Favourite Authors & Genres

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want to select my favourite authors and genres so that I can receive personalized recommendations that match my preferences.

Back of the card:
Users can choose authors/genres while signing up or later in their profile.
Choices can be updated anytime.
Suggestions update automatically based on favourites.
If no favourites are set, the system shows general popular books.

User Story 2 – AI Smart Suggestions

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want AI to suggest books based on what I read and like so that I can easily find new books I’ll enjoy.

Back of the card:
AI looks at reading history, ratings, and time spent.
Suggestions appear on the home screen and refresh regularly.
Users can mark “Not Interested” to refine future results.
For new users, AI suggests books liked by similar readers.

User Story 3 – AI Summary Generation

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want short AI-made summaries of books so that I can quickly decide whether to read or skip the book.

Back of the card:
The book is approved by the admin.
AI generates a short summary for the approved book
User clicks “Generate Summary” on a book.
The already existing summary is fetched by the system and displayed to the user.
Fiction summaries avoid spoilers unless requested.

User Story 4 – AI Scene Generation

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want AI to create pictures of book scenes so that I can imagine the story better.

Back of the card:
The user highlights a passage and requests a scene.
AI generates an image based on the passage.
Users can pick visual styles (sketch, realistic, etc.).

User Story 5 – Genre Reading Visualization

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want to see which genres I read most so that I can track my reading habits.

Back of the card:
The system tags each book with its genre.
A chart shows how many books are read per genre.
Users can filter results by time (month, year, all time).
Clicking a genre displays books read in that category.

User Story 6 – Personalized Notifications & Alerts

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want personalized notifications about new releases and suggestions so that I always have fresh reading options.

Back of the card:
The system sends alerts for new releases or book suggestions.
Alerts link directly to book detail pages.
Users can enable or disable alerts anytime.

User Story 7 – AI-Curated Reading Digest

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want a daily or weekly list of suggested books so that I always have fresh options to read.

Back of the card:
AI generates a small digest of 3–5 books.
Digest is shown in-app or sent by email.
The list updates automatically as the user’s reading evolves.

User Story 8 – Reading Streaks & Personalized Challenges

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want reading streaks and challenges so that I stay motivated to read more.

Back of the card:
The system tracks daily reading streaks.
Challenges are created based on favourite genres (e.g., “Read 5 thrillers this month”).
Progress is shown on the dashboard.
Users earn badges or milestones when challenges are completed.

User Story 9 – Adaptive Learning Recommendations

Front of the card:
 As a user, I want AI to suggest books outside my usual genres so that I can try new topics.

Back of the card:
AI detects gaps in the user’s reading behaviour.
Suggestions appear in a separate “Explore” section.
Users can accept or skip these suggestions.
AI adapts future recommendations based on user response.
